Microsoft is offering a "find me" service as part of its Virtual Earth offering. You can be <a href="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/exit.php?url_id=950&amp;entry_id=433" title="http://www.vnunet.com/vnunet/news/2140354/microsoft-launches-gps-killer" onmouseover="window.status='http://www.vnunet.com/vnunet/news/2140354/microsoft-launches-gps-killer';return true;" onmouseout="window.status='';return true;">found</A> via IP address (think Digital Envoy and other geotargeting tools) or via Wi-Fi. Microsoft has mapping Wi-Fi hotspots (others have too) and claims to be able to locate people to 30 meters. This <a href="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/exit.php?url_id=951&amp;entry_id=433" title="http://www.tomshardware.com/hardnews/20050728_173123.html" onmouseover="window.status='http://www.tomshardware.com/hardnews/20050728_173123.html';return true;" onmouseout="window.status='';return true;">article</A> suggests Google is not far behind with something similar.<br />
