<p>Don't look now but there is a white elephant on the UC exhibit floor. It's called <a href="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/exit.php?url_id=926&amp;entry_id=420" title="http://maps.google.com/" onmouseover="window.status='http://maps.google.com/';return true;" onmouseout="window.status='';return true;">Google Maps</a>. We can talk about it behind its back but we just can't look at it too long. Look folks, there is not really a buzz about it here, but the questions, from those with whom I have spoken, always come up:</p><p>What does it mean for GIS and company's like ESRI? Will it really make a difference to their bottom line? Will users escew ArcIMS and use the Google API to create a quick web map application? Can ArcExplorer and the network of ESRI web services compete with Google Earth?</p><p>Doesn't Google &quot;float the boat&quot; of all GIS companies and location technology in general? Clearly it does because never before have we seen so much ink expended by the mainstream press. Google seems to be in a perpetual beta, always throwing up new things and not telling anyone...but the masses find out anyway. Awareness is key, and whereas for years we have tried to get people to take more notice of our technology sector, the &quot;Google Phenomenon&quot; has done more in six months than what I was able to do in sixteen years when I started the column &quot;GIS in Business&quot; for <em>GIS World Magazine</em> in 1991. The buzz used to be created by Microsoft but now the new kid on the block is causing a fuss.</p><p>Google will NOT impact the GIS business anytime soon and as <a href="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/exit.php?url_id=927&amp;entry_id=420" title="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/402-Quote-of-the-Week.html" onmouseover="window.status='http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/402-Quote-of-the-Week.html';return true;" onmouseout="window.status='';return true;">Mark Cattini</a>, CEO of MapInfo said, &quot;It's certainly very good consumer eye-candy.&quot; Jack Dangermond cautioned me, &quot;don't overhype it&quot; and &quot;It reminds me of LBS.&quot; So, the cautions are valid but it is still hard to ignore the pale pachyderm.</p>     ";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 27 Jul 2005 15:59:00 -0700";s:4:"guid";s:56:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/420-guid.html";s:12:"atom_content";s:2209:"
