<p>Don't look now but there is a white elephant on the UC exhibit floor. It's called <a href="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/exit.php?url_id=926&amp;entry_id=420" title="http://maps.google.com/" onmouseover="window.status='http://maps.google.com/';return true;" onmouseout="window.status='';return true;">Google Maps</a>. We can talk about it behind its back but we just can't look at it too long. Look folks, there is not really a buzz about it here, but the questions, from those with whom I have spoken, always come up:</p><p>What does it mean for GIS and company's like ESRI? Will it really make a difference to their bottom line? Will users escew ArcIMS and use the Google API to create a quick web map application? Can ArcExplorer and the network of ESRI web services compete with Google Earth?</p><p>Doesn't Google &quot;float the boat&quot; of all GIS companies and location technology in general? Clearly it does because never before have we seen so much ink expended by the mainstream press. Google seems to be in a perpetual beta, always throwing up new things and not telling anyone...but the masses find out anyway. Awareness is key, and whereas for years we have tried to get people to take more notice of our technology sector, the &quot;Google Phenomenon&quot; has done more in six months than what I was able to do in sixteen years when I started the column &quot;GIS in Business&quot; for <em>GIS World Magazine</em> in 1991. The buzz used to be created by Microsoft but now the new kid on the block is causing a fuss.</p><p>Google will NOT impact the GIS business anytime soon and as <a href="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/exit.php?url_id=927&amp;entry_id=420" title="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/402-Quote-of-the-Week.html" onmouseover="window.status='http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/402-Quote-of-the-Week.html';return true;" onmouseout="window.status='';return true;">Mark Cattini</a>, CEO of MapInfo said, &quot;It's certainly very good consumer eye-candy.&quot; Jack Dangermond cautioned me, &quot;don't overhype it&quot; and &quot;It reminds me of LBS.&quot; So, the cautions are valid but it is still hard to ignore the pale pachyderm.</p>     ";}i:13;a:10:{s:5:"title";s:33:"MSN Virtual Earth Vs. Google Maps";s:4:"link";s:85:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/425-MSN-Virtual-Earth-Vs.-Google-Maps.html";s:8:"comments";s:94:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/425-MSN-Virtual-Earth-Vs.-Google-Maps.html#comments";s:3:"wfw";a:2:{s:7:"comment";s:56:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/wfwcomment.php?cid=425";s:10:"commentrss";s:75:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/rss.php?version=2.0&type=comments&cid=425";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"2";}s:6:"author";s:42:"adena@directionsmag.com (Adena Schutzberg)";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:469:"
Want to see them go head to head? You can at this <a href="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/exit.php?url_id=929&amp;entry_id=425" title="http://www.jonasson.org/maps/" onmouseover="window.status='http://www.jonasson.org/maps/';return true;" onmouseout="window.status='';return true;">website</A>. MSN is on the left, Google on the right. On quick look, Google has more road labels and one-way street indicators. Further, its bright yellow labels really stand out.    ";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 27 Jul 2005 15:07:57 -0700";s:4:"guid";s:56:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/425-guid.html";s:12:"atom_content";s:469:"
Want to see them go head to head? You can at this <a href="http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/exit.php?url_id=929&amp;entry_id=425" title="http://www.jonasson.org/maps/" onmouseover="window.status='http://www.jonasson.org/maps/';return true;" onmouseout="window.status='';return true;">website</A>. MSN is on the left, Google on the right. On quick look, Google has more road labels and one-way street indicators. Further, its bright yellow labels really stand out.    ";}i:14;a:10:{s:5:"title";s:45:"ESRI-UC - Notes from ArcGIS Server - an Intro";s:4:"link";s:93:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/424-ESRI-UC-Notes-from-ArcGIS-Server-an-Intro.html";s:8:"comments";s:102:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/424-ESRI-UC-Notes-from-ArcGIS-Server-an-Intro.html#comments";s:3:"wfw";a:2:{s:7:"comment";s:56:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/wfwcomment.php?cid=424";s:10:"commentrss";s:75:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/rss.php?version=2.0&type=comments&cid=424";}s:5:"slash";a:1:{s:8:"comments";s:1:"0";}s:6:"author";s:16:" (Julia Harrell)";s:7:"content";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";s:7822:"
Tuesday 8:30 session - ArcGIS Server - an Intro by Jeff Archer &amp; Eric Miller<br />
<br />
Server side web apps &amp; services for focused GIS tasks using ArcObjects. SOAP/XML, .Net and Java App Development Framework (ADF).<br />
<br />
You can use them to integrate full-function GIS capability into enterprise information systems. <br />
<br />
2 parts: ADF (Web controls, convenience classes, API), GIS Server that hosts server objects for use by web apps running within .Net and J2EE application servers.<br />
<br />
Unix now supported at 9.1 for Java<br />
<br />
Solaris 8.9  RedHad Enterprise 3 &amp; Suse Enterprise 9 Some windows support required - need ArcCatalog to administer and authentication must be on Windows PC.<br />
<br />
Spatial, 3D &amp; Network Analyst extension avail. (No Globe, must wait until 9.2), can do drive time and service area analysis now over the Web.<br />
<br />
Designed for enterprise implementations for distributed GIS access, GIS centric applications with advanced analysis functionality.<br />
Not really designed for map publishing - use ArcIMS for that.<br />
Good for short transaction editing and basic attribute update over the web - can reduce the need to manage many ArcGIS desktop installations for basic users. Great for centralizing GIS Functionality.<br />
<br />
Good for centralized services - gazateer, image and basemap services, route generation &amp; geocoding, proximity searches. easy to integrate into ERP systems, executive reporting. Good for embedding GIS into established workflows.<br />
<br />
<B>Soap/XML Web Services</B><br />
<br />
You can publish your own Soap/XML web services in a catalog and allow other developers in your organization to utilize these GIS services in all of their apps.<br />
<br />
Can consume output of other GIS web services in your apps too.<br />
<br />
Can do short or long transactions in geodatabase editing.<br />
Can checkout a version, save to personal geodb, make edits, then post edits back to SDE.<br />
<br />
Uses simple data types (strings, integers, etc.)<br />
<br />
Web services can chain multiple operations into a single processing chunk, or you can have multiple services and invoke them in your own processing order and present a final output map or list of attribute results.<br />
<br />
<B>ArcGIS Server Web Services</B><br />
<br />
Works with more complex data types using ArcObjects<br />
<br />
Can do advanced analysis such as cost surface or suitability modeling using spatial analyst over the web now.<br />
<br />
Templates are included in the ADF - one for geodatabase editing is included.<br />
<br />
Can be JSPs or ASP.Net Apps. <br />
<br />
Can add polygons to a geodb by digitizing on screen. <br />
<br />
Users can sketch in desired additions to their infrastructure as well as capturing existing.<br />
can embed workflow control and have mgrs log in and approve or reject redlined markups by employees and changes will be posted to geodb.<br />
<br />
Collaborative worklfow from distributed locations all going to the same geodb.<br />
<br />
Look for all the demos on the EDN website.<br />
<br />
<B>The Guts of GIS Server</B><br />
<br />
Collection of process that run in background to publish ArcObjects functionality.<br />
A webserver is needed.  MUST use ArcCatalog to administer ArcGIS Server.<br />
GIS Server can run across multiple machines.<br />
Can use thick desktop clients or web apps to access these.<br />
<br />
Server object manager (SOM) is the broker. <br />
<br />
Server Object Container (SOC) hosts the ArcObjects functionality. <br />
Similar to the ArcIMS spatial server.<br />
<br />
All services published support the SOAP Tooklit, can discover them and see all them methods in a Web browser with the right request.<br />
<br />
Powered by a multi threaded GIS engine with an extensive API, full<br />
geodatabase functionality and all the geometry models. Easy to install and administer - out of the box. Administer with ArcCatagog to start server objects, add new servers, load balance apps. You can build your own custom administration dashboards and do away w/ ArcCatalog.<br />
Takes full advantage of OS, .Net and Java security features, including easier to use controls. Works well w/ firewalls and windows integrated authentication. Provides a clean separation between client access to webserver and webserver access to the GIS server (multilayer security)<br />
ALL access to the GIS Server is authenticated.<br />
<br />
Very scaleable - supports pooling and distribution of server objects across machines and CPUS. can use a farm of low cost machines or a blade center.<br />
<br />
Supports WSDL - supports all the major Java App servers (Websphere, Weblogic,<br />
etc)<br />
No need to change app when adding new CPUs.<br />
<br />
Can host virtual IP addresses with ArcGIS server.<br />
<br />
Desktop ArcObjects code will run on the web except for UI components. You will have to build your own user interface.<br />
<br />
You will install the ADF runtime (proxies to ArcObjects) on the Web application server. They will contact the SOC on the GIS app server which will process and send results back to web app server.<br />
<br />
It can actually be a statefull connection for extended processing <br />
operations.<br />
<br />
9.1 objects types: (more types available in 9.2)<br />
<br />
Mapserver (describe display layers and maps, query, identify, analyze features,<br />
includes the geodatabase connection to the data itself.<br />
<br />
Geocode server objects: publish a desktop locator, supports standardization, address validation, single and batch geocoding, and reverse geocoding. You can create a custom locator object on the desktop and use with the geocoding service.<br />
<br />
Publishing methods - pooled and non-pooled. Pooled can limit number of instances (simple transaction model 1:M connection)<br />
<br />
Non pooled must be used for complex disconnected editing. 1:1 deeply<br />
stateful connection for long times.<br />
<br />
<B>Administer with ArcCatalog</B><br />
<br />
add SOM machine (GIS Server) to ArcCatalog. (can be local or internet)<br />
and add some or all of its available services. Set logging parameters<br />
and server oject startup time in secodns ( for slow geodb connections),<br />
hosts (extra SOC machines).Directores (where to route output on webserver),<br />
statistics (performance optimization diagnosis tool) <br />
set pooling parameters, manage processes, isolation mode, recycling properties<br />
(for recovering memory leaks)<br />
<br />
<B>Security</B><br />
<br />
service authentication to gis server<br />
authentication of GIS Server to all the resources it uses<br />
authenticatgion of ArcCatalog to access GIS Server<br />
<br />
GIS Server runs using a distinguished OS account. You should create an account for GIS Server so it can access SDE connections.<br />
<br />
agsuser group - any user who connects to ArcGIS server will have the same privleges as the arcgis server account. need to look at limiting the privileges of ArcGIS Server to minimum necessary.<br />
<br />
Can have anonymous users with authentication handled transparently inside the application if you don't want users to have to login. or can manage different levels of user groups for access.<br />
<br />
EDN - $1500 / yr subscription -  suggested for ArcGIS developers to get started. You can develop first, then deploy. You don't' get ArcGIS desktop with EDN, but you will need it. ESRI will convert existing developer seats to EDN subscriptions with cost reduction.<br />
<br />
You get the EDN resource binder with all product CDs, documentation<br />
library, (ENGINE devel kit &amp; runtime, Server .net &amp; Java ADFs, <br />
ArcIMS, SDE, ArcWeb Services)<br />
    ";}s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 27 Jul 2005 09:59:55 -0700";s:4:"guid";s:56:"http://www.directionsmag.com/blog/archives/424-guid.html";s:12:"atom_content";s:7822:"
